-- Oil Options Volatility Rises as Futures Decline Third Day
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-05-23T17:38:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-23/oil-options-volatility-rises-as-futures-decline-third-day.html
Crude oil options volatility rose as
the underlying futures fell for a third straight session.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
July, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 22.5 percent at 1:35 p.m. on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, up from 22.06 percent yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for July delivery fell $1.01,
or 1.1 percent, to $93.27 a barrel.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
July $90 puts, which rose 19 cents to $1.10 a barrel on volume
of 7,473 contracts at 1:35 p.m. in New York. September $85 puts
were the second-most active, advancing 26 cents to $1.54 on
6,099 lots.  Puts accounted for 60 percent of electronic trading volume
today and made up 70 percent of the prior trading dayâ€™s volume
of 149,933 contracts.  July $88 puts were the most-active options traded in the
previous session, with 12,358 contracts changing hands. They
gained 22 cents to 58 cents a barrel. July $85 puts rose 11
cents to 29 cents a barrel on 10,645 lots.  Open interest was highest for July $90 puts with 42,138
contracts. Next were December $105 calls with 38,324 lots and
July $110 calls with 35,177.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
